In April 2005, Fukuhara replaced compatriot Aya Umemura and became the highest-ranked Japanese female on the ITTF World Ranking list.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ai-chan is top-ranked Japanese |url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/sp20050406a2.html |newspaper=The Japan Times |date=6 April 2005 |accessdate=8 January 2011}}</ref> She advanced to the semifinals at the 2005 [[Table Tennis World Cup|Women's World Cup]], losing to [[Guo Yan]] in the semifinals but beating [[Tie Ya Na]] in the third place match.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ittf.com/_front_page/ittf_full_story1.asp?ID=8276&Competition_ID=1544& |title=The Mental Edge |author=Steve Dainton |author2=Ian Marshall |date=15 December 2005 |publisher=ITTF |accessdate=8 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ittf.com/_front_page/ittf_full_story1.asp?ID=8280&Competition_ID=1544& |title=Unbeatable |author=Steve Dainton |author2=Ian Marshall |date=15 December 2005 |publisher=ITTF |accessdate=8 January 2011}}</ref>

Fukuhara was directly qualified for the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] through world ranking.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ittf.com/competitions/competitions2.asp?Competition_ID=1665&category=OG |title=2008 Olympic Games |publisher=ITTF |accessdate=8 January 2011}}</ref> She was chosen as the national flag bearer for Japan at the Olympic Games in Beijing, China.<ref name="Wu 2008">{{cite news |title=Fukuhara looks to end Japan's medal drought |author=Wu Zhi |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2008-08/04/content_8951237.htm |newspaper=Xinhua |date=4 August 2008 |accessdate=6 January 2011}}</ref> Fukuhara teamed up with [[Sayaka Hirano]] and [[Haruna Fukuoka]] at the women's team event. They reached the bronze medal contest but lost to South Korea. In the singles event, Fukuhara advanced to round of 16, losing to gold medalist [[Zhang Yining]].

She also qualified directly for the [[2012 Summer Olympics|London 2012 Olympic Games]] with her world ranking in June 2011, but lost to [[Ding Ning]] on 31 July 2012, (13-15, 6-11, 6-11, and 4-11).<ref>http://www.ittf.com/Stories/pictures/qualified_players_london_w.pdf ITTF - Players qualified for the 2012 London Olympic Games (accessed 6 December 2011).</ref> At the [[Table tennis at the 2012 Summer Olympics <U+2013> Women's team|Women's Team Event]] semi-finals, she defeated [[Feng Tianwei]] (11-9, 11-6, 5-11 and 11-9) in the first match which eventually helped Japan reached their first table tennis finals in the Olympics over Singapore.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.london2012.com/table-tennis/event/women-team/match=ttw400202/index.html |title=Women's Team Event semi-finals 1 results |accessdate=6 August 2012}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.london2012.com/news/articles/japanese-women-make-through.html |title=Japanese women make it through |accessdate=6 August 2012}}</ref> However, Japan failed to defeat China in the finals but got her first [[silver medal]] ever in table tennis.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.london2012.com/table-tennis/event/women-team/match=ttw400101/index.html |title=Women's team finals results accessdate=8 August 2012}}</ref>

===Hong Kong 2009 East Asian Games===
Ai Fukuhara won Table Tennis Women's Doubles with [[Kasumi Ishikawa]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Japanese Fukuhara/Ishikawa win women's table tennis doubles at EAG |author=Deng Shasha |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/sports/2009-12/07/c_13140026.htm |newspaper=Xinhua |date=7 December 2009 |accessdate=6 January 2011}}</ref>

===ITTF Kuwait Open 2010===
The Kuwait Open 2010 would be Ai's most fruitful competition at that time. On the way to the finals, she caused numerous upsets.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ittf.com/competitions/competitions2.asp?Competition_ID=1912&category=pt |title=2010 Kuwait Open - ITTF Pro Tour |publisher=ITTF |accessdate=6 January 2011}}</ref> Starting off, she upset China by defeating [[Guo Yue (table tennis)|Guo Yue]]. Later on, she played Singapore's [[Wang Yuegu]], where Ai eventually won 4-2. After two shocking wins, Ai went on to cause another upset to China by beating the experienced top-spin specialist, [[Guo Yan]]. In the highly lauded and suspenseful final, she nearly defeated China's top seed [[Liu Shiwen]], but lost 3-4.

== Popularity ==
Her first name, Ai, means "love" and she is often referred to as "Ai-chan" (<U+611B><U+3061><U+3083><U+3093>) in Japan. Her youth and talent has made her a popular sports star in Japan. Ai Fukuhara has appeared in two Japanese table tennis video games, including ''Ikuze! Onsen Takky<U+016B>!!'' (Do it! Hot Spring Table Tennis!!), released on 21 December 2001 and ''Fukuhara Ai No Takky<U+016B> Icchokusen'' (Ai Fukuhara's Table Tennis), released on 24 June 2004, both for the [[PlayStation 2]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ps2.ign.com/objects/689/689710.html?about_tab=6 |title=Ai Fukuhara's Ping Pong |work=ign.com |accessdate=6 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://ps2.ign.com/articles/135/135673p1.html |title=Ikuze! Onsen Takkyu |author= |date=1 December 2000 |work=ign.com |accessdate=6 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.play-asia.com/paOS-13-71-45-49-en-70-22b.html |title=Got to do! Hot Spring Table Tennis |work=play-asia.com |accessdate=6 January 2011}}</ref> She carried the Olympic flame when it traveled to Tokyo in 2004.<ref>{{cite news |title='Ai-chan' replaces 'Mr. Giants' in Tokyo Olympic torch relay |url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/sp20040502a2.html |newspaper=The Japan Times |date=2 May 2004 |accessdate=8 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Olympic flame carried through Tokyo on way to Athens |url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20040607a2.html |newspaper=The Japan Times |date=7 June 2004 |accessdate=8 January 2011}}</ref> She carried the torch once again for the [[Beijing Olympic Games]] in 2008, and was the flag bearer for the Japanese national team at the Opening Ceremonies.<ref name="Wu 2008"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Torch security smothers relay |url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20080427a1.html |newspaper=Kyodo News |date=27 April 2008 |accessdate=8 January 2011}}</ref>

Since she has been playing table tennis in China from a very young age, Fukuhara can speak fluent [[Mandarin Chinese]] with a [[Northeast China|Northeastern]] accent. Therefore she has greater popularity in China than most other table tennis players from outside of China.<ref>{{cite news |title=Japanese belle Fukuhara wins over China |author=Simon Rabinovitch |url=http://www.reuters.com/article/idUSPEK17920920080814 |newspaper=Reuters |date=14 August 2008 |accessdate=7 January 2011}}</ref> In an incident widely reported by the Chinese media, she wrote down "<U+4E2D><U+65E5><U+53CB><U+597D>" (meaning "Sino-Japanese friendship" in both Chinese and Japanese) when meeting [[Wang Yi (politician)|Wang Yi]], then Chinese ambassador to Japan, at the height of the [[2005 anti-Japanese demonstrations]].<ref>{{cite news |title=<U+798F><U+539F><U+7231><U+FF1A><U+4E2D><U+65E5><U+6C11><U+95F4><U+82B1><U+5B63>"<U+5927><U+4F7F>" |author= |author2= |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/world/2005-04/29/content_2894570.htm |newspaper=Xinhua |date=29 April 2005 |accessdate=6 January 2011 |language=Chinese}}</ref>

In July 2005, Fukuhara guest-starred alongside Chinese actor [[Jackie Chan]] during the opening of a photograph exhibition, in [[Roppongi Hills]], to celebrate 60 years of peaceful coexistence between China and Japan.<ref>{{cite news |title=Photo exhibition on Japan-China friendship starts in Tokyo |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2005-07/28/content_3282653.htm |newspaper=Xinhua |date=28 July 2005 |accessdate=6 January 2011}}</ref> During Chinese President [[Hu Jintao]]'s visit to Japan in 2008, Hu played table tennis with Fukuhara at [[Waseda University]].<ref>{{cite news |title=National Chairman Hu Jintao speaks of future-oriented amity to next term's Japanese and Chinese youth |url=http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/adv/wol/dy/news/news_080514.htm |newspaper=Yomiuri Shimbun |date=14 May 2008 |accessdate=6 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=President Hu plays pingpong in Japan |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2008-05/09/content_8133041.htm |newspaper=Xinhua |date=9 May 2008 |accessdate=6 January 2011}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Fukuhara attended Aomori Yamada Junior High School and graduated from Aomori Yamada High School in 2007. Both schools are located in the city of [[Aomori, Aomori|Aomori]] in [[Aomori Prefecture]]. In 2007, she enrolled in [[Waseda University]]'s sports science department; she decided to drop out in 2010 to focus on her table tennis competitions.<ref>{{cite news |title=Fukuhara drops out of Waseda, shifts focus to London Olympics |url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/sp20100306a1.html |newspaper=Kyodo News |date=6 March 2010 |accessdate=6 January 2011}}</ref>

